Power BI</h1><p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; padding: 0px; line-height: 1.714; letter-spacing: -0.005em;"></p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;">The <em style="color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" data-renderer-mark="true">Master/Main&nbsp;</em><span style="color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">branch should always be considered to represent the latest code deployed to production. During day to day development, the&nbsp;</span><em style="border-color: var(--border-color); color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" data-renderer-mark="true">Master&nbsp;</em><span style="color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">branch will not be interacted with.&nbsp;</span></font><font style="font-size: 12px;">When the source code in the <em style="color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" data-renderer-mark="true">develop </em><span style="color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">branch is stable and has been deployed, all of the changes will be merged into&nbsp;</span><em style="border-color: var(--border-color); color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" data-renderer-mark="true">Master/Main&nbsp;</em><span style="color: rgb(23, 43, 77); letter-spacing: -0.08px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">and tagged with a release number.</span></font></p><font style="font-size: 12px;">Supporting branches are used to aid parallel development between team members, ease tracking of features, and to assist in quickly fixing live production problems. Unlike the main branches, these branches always have a life time, since they will be removed eventually.<br></font><font style="font-size: 12px;">The different types of branches we may use are:<br></font><p></p><ul><li><font style="font-size: 12px;"><font style="font-size: 12px;">Feature branches</font></font></li><li><font style="font-size: 12px;"><font style="font-size: 12px;">Bug branches</font></font></li><li><font style="font-size: 12px;"><font style="font-size: 12px;">Hotfix branches</font></font></li></ul>When merging into the <i>Master/Main</i> branch, the incoming branch should be deleted afterwards.<br><p></p>" style="text;html=1;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;spacing=5;spacingTop=-20;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="10" y="380" width="810" height="240" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> </mxfile>

div.p:
The intent is that the content on PowerBI service's production workspaces is parallel to the content stored in the version controlled "remote" repository's MAIN branch.
This is so only properly approved reports are show to users.

div.p: The MAIN branch of the Remote Repository contains the approved reports, which are known to be stable and showing correct information.

New reports and modifications are brought into the MAIN branch through Merges, per Page: Branching Strategy.
(These merges are done via Pull Request if using a Git repositiory management tool like "AzureDevOps" or "GitHub")
